Subject: Hodge Anchor Realization Gate 001

Description: First application of the Hodge Anchor Realization Gate to the source document's memory-anchor proposition.

& [GateFrame] is the scoped check
  + [tool] is C:\Project\Pinky\.sop\platform\seven_math_problems\proof_inquiry\Hodge_Anchor_Realization_Gate.sop
  + [source_shape] is memory anchors in a curved field resolve into rational algebraic behavior
  + [formal_target] is rational Hodge class realized by algebraic cycles
  + [proof_status] is inquiry_candidate_not_proof

& [SourceSet] is research evidence
  + [source_001] is Clay Mathematics Institute Hodge problem statement
    = url: https://www.claymath.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/hodge.pdf
    = evidence: on a projective non-singular algebraic variety over C, any Hodge class is conjectured to be a rational linear combination of algebraic cycle classes
  + [source_002] is Voisin "The Hodge conjecture"
    = url: https://webusers.imj-prg.fr/~claire.voisin/Articlesweb/voisinhodge.pdf
    = evidence: the conjecture relates topological/Betti cohomology data, complex Hodge structure, and algebraic cycles
  + [source_003] is "Known cases of the Hodge conjecture"
    = url: https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2105.04695
    = evidence: known cases exist but the general conjecture remains open
  + [source_004] is Clay Hodge problem statement remarks
    = evidence: divisor/codimension-one type results are covered by Lefschetz (1,1) style theorem, while the general higher-codimension statement remains open
  + [source_005] is Totaro-style integral Hodge counterexample literature
    = url: https://www.math.ucla.edu/~totaro/papers/public_html/integral.pdf
    = evidence: integral Hodge variants can fail, so rational/integral boundaries must stay explicit

